A Bone House is also fascinated after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn up fish mills.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "Knechenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of sheds and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with beautiful lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and beings.
It is only on closer observation that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
During the night, the entire facade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the brightness of the colors.
The same winding lines and engulfed shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railers, decorative elements of doors, even look holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively Passeig de Grácia No. 43 shopping street was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877 that architects Emilio Sala Cortese performed.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
However, the house Casa Batlló did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade were created on its drawing board.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Park Güell, which also contains other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nicknames "Knechenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "equivalent house".
It is also said that at the very top of the building is the sword of St. Georg, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculpture elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system, unique for the time being, with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre already seems to be her 45-degree inclination.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at the time and was by no means allowed by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he had given about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when the city fathers were finished, they were so horrified that they demanded remedial action.
Among other things, the councillors also found that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the city quarter's request was made by Josep Batlló to approve the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was granted to him immediately.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Through the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could chat comfortably without having to miss a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors by Gaudí's reconstruction in addition to a new facade.
Gaudí's play is also impressive with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is disguised and the light courts.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that, on the contrary, absorb the sunlight.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can visit everyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners did not decide on this step until the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a rather sensitive business, the visits were maintained, and they also extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the building monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the admission prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
