A longer finger than ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are clearly at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the cancer research institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health stress, Mrs. Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain persecuted more than 1500 prostate cancer patients, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger was shorter in the right hand than the ring finger.
For these men the same probability of prostate cancer as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were equal in length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men to 60 percent even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are already in the prenatal age, clearly reflects the different mirrors of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that this study was well-known to him, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the cancer risk to be "full".
