Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has opted for the maintenance of the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the whole of the European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adaptation measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary workers or the abolition of the EUR 426 for unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefit, up to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, with the help of former President Felipe González, the Deputy Head of Government, Elena Salgado, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How can these processes be understood?
It should be anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefinition of the euro.
Germany is taking on a fundamental new perspective on the design of our future, which collides with the maintenance of the old-fashioned traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, one begins to speculate in Germany about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south had to leave the euro area.
The Second: The re-introduction of the German Mark - although it is now more like Science Fiction -, supported by a large majority of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reorganisation of the euro according to German proposals. This means: greater macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that exceed the targets; possibly the adjustment of some countries and the extension of the cost of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government drew out of the sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening from 2016.
This was the first sign of the disintegrating between what Germany considered necessary (severe tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign put the Central European country when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion were absolutely against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has come out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country's salvation and, at the same time, for private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it was driving the Irish crisis and all the following forward.
But their proposal, although sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new currency area in which the infringinging countries will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves ineffective and in this case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard growth rate, with high savings and investment rates, consumption moderation, improved productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as pointed out by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we'd do bad not to understand.
It's not just about cutting the state deficit down to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulences will go into more calm.
And that we will use the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this too, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in one's own home has set its course.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like something would change.
Among the options considered, we should not exclude the fact that we should leave the euro area fully stuffed with few serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
Sports and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show ingenuity, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The exclusion in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) supposedly led to a lot of ink being poured over whether it was an unsportable act or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is common knowledge, the two players lost time a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty at the next game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next stage without cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club's coach José Mourinho with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules, but followed in this sport.
Part of the debate on the case presented is based on the fact that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who pretends in his anthem of grace and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role in this, and the dramatisation by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behaviour, which is not explicitly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a regular circumvention. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be examined.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponent, an aspect that was not threatened by these actions, for it was no aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking an unjustified advantage of the opposing team, and that didn't happen either.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by cheating or evasion, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible to be punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and accepted the sanction joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage the infringers drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was not brought into a more unfavorable situation or gained benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players begin the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it's a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually leave. Moreover, the players receive a penalty with this procedure and move into the second card cycle, in which they leave for card accumulation with a card less than in the first cycle.
It is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Finally, such actions are not directed against the sports spirit, including strategic decisions to benefit from the rules as much as possible.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of regular circumvention), but rather they wanted to choose when they were going to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing a punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemics was created as a result of two factors: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked transmission of rules.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
