China continues to maintain its greenhouse gas reduction targets
At COP16, the representative of China stated that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon traces and that it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China holds its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, says Su Wei, the representative of this country at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th World Climate Summit of the United Nations (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon traces and to convert its industry.
He stated that in the last four years, his country had invested 245 million dollars to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work on this issue together with the international community.
He explained that the Chinese strategy for climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all aspects, progress has been made, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the objectives of reducing the emissions of gases.
On the other hand, it stressed that in China the authorities of the states cooperated with those of the central state and the municipalities in order to achieve the objectives of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he pointed out, some multiannual plans have already been launched or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the programme for the effective use of energy, which has been introduced over the last five years and received investment from the United Nations (UNO), the government and private hands.
There is also a project at the provincial level on climate change, another on the exchange of traditional bulbs by energy-saving bulbs and another on mitigating and adapting, he said.
Martin Krol, Scientific Government Advisor on climate change in this country, confirmed that China's efforts would be far greater than generally assumed.
He pointed out that the per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China amount to six tonnes per person, while in the United States it is 100 tonnes. China is responsible for a nine-percent total contribution to environmental pollution.
