Yesterday, in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to reducing greenhouse gas emissions (CFCs), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction obligations of the developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs delivered to the earth due to the lighting would be avoided if the white-burning pears, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or even better, by light diodes (LED).
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases from the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major exhaust gas emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that were supposed to lower global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt should be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the increase in climate by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 in order to prevent it from being out of control.
In the white-burning pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact bulbs the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs this energy requirement is reduced by two times.
The compact fluorescent bulbs hold between 6000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those put on the market by Philips this week - this company has, by the way, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-burning pear, which gives an indication of the savings potential of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that the completely new bulbs give very little heat, they can also work with a rule resistance.
