Several specialists have shown that compact light bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and therefore have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in the developing countries, except for producers, provide an acceptance point.
According to the report, however, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet does not represent the compact bulb bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would gain from this international programme.
