These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - have been examined as well as wethereries of laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is flattering: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or probably carcinogenic and five as safe cardiac substances, as well as 37 substances with endocrine interference factors, according to studies of several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded in the nearing total of cases, this survey is very well taken from the fact that the reality in which the consumer may be exposed to carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine interference factors is worrying," the association notes.
Already at breakfast alone, the butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proved to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormone system.
The apple imported from Brazil, as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, including in lunch, where the study has identified traces of an insecticide strictly banned in the EU.
Furthermore, the hack steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were spewed.
In tap water, analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroforms.
During dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was the "richest", and even the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not unladen.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is probably undervalued", the study says.
The "Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts" (EE-LV) has in turn proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increasing of civilizational diseases".
In July, a European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) study identified 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables, which are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
